library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)
library(scales)
airbnb_data<-read.csv("../Data/Aemf1.csv")

`

# Create the ggplot visualization
gg <- ggplot(airbnb_data, aes(x = log(Metro.Distance..km. + 1), y = log(Price + 1))) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.4, color="#6BAED6") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "#D73027",alpha=0.7) +
  labs(title = expression(italic("Relationship Between Proximity to Metro Station and Airbnb Price")),
       x = "Distance to Metro Station (log km)",
       y = "Airbnb Price (log)",
       caption = "Data Source: Keggle") +
  facet_wrap(~ City, scales = "free") +
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::number_format(accuracy = 0.1)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::number_format(accuracy = 0.1)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(  # Set panel background color
        strip.text = element_text(size = 12, face = "bold"),  
        legend.title = element_text(size = 8),
        plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 16),
        axis.title.x = element_text(size = 14),  # Adjust x-axis title size
        axis.title.y = element_text(size = 14))

# Print the ggplot object
print(gg)

# Save the ggplot object as a variable
gg <- gg

The visualization explores the relationship between the proximity of Airbnb listings to metro stations and their corresponding prices across multiple cities. It consists of a series of scatter plots, each representing a different city, with the x-axis displaying the logarithmically transformed distance to the nearest metro station (in kilometers) and the y-axis showing the logarithmically transformed Airbnb prices.

The scatter points are semi-transparent to handle overlapping data points, making it easier to discern clusters and trends. Overall, this visualization offers valuable insights into how the distance to metro stations correlates with Airbnb listing prices, with specific patterns emerging in different cities.
